ntic Rim, these were independent national societies whose cultural self-image was nevertheless marked by a sense of difference. Barshay presents a historical overview of major Japanese trends and treats two of the most powerful streams of Japanese social science, one associated with Marxism, the other with Modernism (kindaishugi), whose most representative figure is the late Maruyama Masao. Demonstrating that a sense of developmental alienation shaped the thinking of social scientists in both streams, the author argues that they provided Japanese social science with moments of shared self-understanding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracyzJapanxHistory. 0aIntellectualszJapanxHistory. 0aPolitical culturezJapanxHistory. 0aSocial scienceszJapanxHistory. 0aSocialismzJapan. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aatlantic rim.  acivil society.  acultural self image.  adevelopment.  adevelopmental alienation.  aempires.  aethics.  agermany.  ajapan.  ajapanese capitalism.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese empire.  ajapanese social sciences.  ajapanese society.  akindaishugi.  amaruyama masao.  amarxism.  amodernism.  amodernity.  anational society.  apolitical economy.  apolitical thinker.  apolitics.  apostwar japan.  apre revolutionary russia.  arationalization.  aself understanding.  asense of difference.  auno kozo.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023645540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094133540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520941335/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_Y